A ⊗ B = {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,2), (2,3), (2,4), (3,2), (3,3), (3,4)}

Now, let's find B △ B, which represents the symmetric difference of B with itself. The symmetric difference is the set of elements that are in either B or B, but not in both.

B △ B = {}

Now, let's find (A ⊗ B) △ B. Since B is a set of single elements and (A ⊗ B) is a set of ordered pairs, their symmetric difference will be the same as the union of the two sets, as there are no common elements between them.

(A ⊗ B) △ B = {(1,2), (1,3), (1,4), (2,2), (2,3), (2,4), (3,2), (3,3), (3,4), 2, 3, 4}

Finally, let's find A ⊗ (B △ B). Since B △ B = {}, the Cartesian product of A and the empty set will also be an empty set.

A ⊗ (B △ B) = {}
